103
00:05:47,689 --> 00:05:51,943
in the proper direction,
of the direction of the velocity vector

104
00:05:51,943 --> 00:05:55,394
of that planet around the Sun,
in order to escape the solar system.

105
00:05:56,478 --> 00:06:00,166
Here we've an example
of the preceding graph.

106
00:06:00,166 --> 00:06:02,954
The escape velocity
out of the solar system

107
00:06:02,954 --> 00:06:06,900
from Mercury's orbit is about 68 km/s,

108
00:06:07,559 --> 00:06:11,583
but Mercury itself has an average,

109
00:06:11,583 --> 00:06:13,226
it has somewhat of an elliptical orbit,

110
00:06:13,226 --> 00:06:17,007
but average orbital velocity of 48 km/s,

111
00:06:17,007 --> 00:06:22,022
so the transfer velocity out of
the solar system from Mercury's orbit

112
00:06:22,022 --> 00:06:25,724
is the difference between the two,
which is 20 km/s.

113
00:06:25,724 --> 00:06:29,947
Now, the escape velocity from
that very, very small planet, Mercury,

114
00:06:29,947 --> 00:06:34,227
is only 3.5 km/s, so in order
from the surface of Mercury

115
00:06:34,227 --> 00:06:38,127
to escape the solar system
in this two-step process,

116
00:06:38,127 --> 00:06:41,367
you have to add
the two, 20 km/s plus 3.5

117
00:06:41,367 --> 00:06:44,843
which gives you 23.5 km/s.

118
00:06:45,124 --> 00:06:47,349
Now, there is a somewhat
more efficient way

119
00:06:47,349 --> 00:06:49,902
to do this exercise
from the surface of Mercury:

120
00:06:49,902 --> 00:06:53,091
you can give one kick,
instead of the two-step approach.

121
00:06:53,091 --> 00:06:55,325
One kick, and it's
a little more efficient.

122
00:06:55,325 --> 00:06:59,078
You'll find a somewhat
smaller value than the 23.5,

123
00:06:59,078 --> 00:07:02,280
but this is at least one way
to escape the solar system

124
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:03,945
from the surface of Mercury.

125
00:07:04,603 --> 00:07:09,117
Now, it happened that escape velocity
versus direction of escape,

126
00:07:09,577 --> 00:07:12,776
whatever direction you choose
from a distance,

127
00:07:13,701 --> 00:07:17,057
a position of the distance <i>r</i>
from the center of the Earth,

128
00:07:17,057 --> 00:07:20,306
whatever direction you choose,
if you have the escape velocity

129
00:07:20,306 --> 00:07:22,456
you are going to infinity
with a zero velocity.

130
00:07:22,466 --> 00:07:24,077
You can do it straight up.

131
00:07:24,402 --> 00:07:27,687
If you're at this point,
very close to the surface of the Earth,

132
00:07:27,687 --> 00:07:30,574
